Will 2025’s L1s and L2s Outperform, or Repeat 2024’s Underperformance?

Kinji Steimetz
Chris Davis
Andrew Dyer

Feb 7, 2025 ⋅  8 min read

As the AI agent narrative winds down, the crypto market is shifting its focus to the next speculative frontier. One area drawing attention is the upcoming launch of alternative Layer 1s and Layer 2s expected in early 2025. Projects like Berachain, MegaETH, and Monad are among the most anticipated, each introducing new execution environments that aim to attract users and liquidity. However, whether these chains will succeed where others have struggled remains uncertain.

The enthusiasm surrounding these new chains comes with a degree of skepticism, particularly in light of the performance of similar projects launched in 2024. To say these earlier L1 and L2 projects underperformed might be an understatement. Of the notable launches, Hyperliquid is the only project that delivered positive returns post-TGE. In contrast, zkSync, the next best performer, is down roughly 47% since its TGE in June, while tokens like Blast, Mode, and Starknet have each depreciated by over 70%. This widespread underperformance suggests that the initial excitement around new execution environments hasn’t translated into lasting market interest or user adoption.

Adding to the concerns, many of these chains have experienced significant declines in TVL after their token launches. This indicates not only weak token demand but also challenges in attracting and retaining users and liquidity. For instance, Scroll and Blast have both seen their TVL drop by more than 80% since their respective TGEs. Across the board, the 2024 launches have largely failed to capture sustained attention.

Hyperliquid, however, stands as an exception. Both its token price and TVL have increased by over 280% and 115%, respectively, post-TGE. This suggests that while the broader market has been cautious about new L1s and L2s, there is potential for specific projects to generate structural demand if they offer compelling fundamentals and user engagement.

As the next round of chains prepares to launch in Q1, the key question is whether they can outperform both fundamentally and in token price, or if they will follow the same trajectory as many of their 2024 counterparts.

Compare Monad, MegaETH and Berachain

Kinji (@SteimetzKinji)

The upcoming wave of execution environments, including new L1s and L2s, will likely face the same challenges as their 2024 predecessors. The primary issue is the surplus of blockspace. The initial rise of alternative L1s like Solana, Avalanche, and Terra was largely a response to Ethereum’s congestion, which priced out many users. That dynamic doesn’t exist today—gas fees remain manageable for most, and there’s no clear sign of an impending surge in demand that would force users to migrate to new chains. Without a major, unforeseen shift in blockspace demand, these new protocols will need to create their own demand rather than relying on spillover effects from network congestion.

This leads to a second issue: most of these new chains focus on high TPS and EVM compatibility, but those features alone don’t drive the development of differentiated applications. While some applications require a minimum level of throughput, existing chains like Solana and Base already meet those needs. Given the choice, developers are more likely to build on established chains with active users and deeper liquidity rather than gamble on a new environment with little traction. The network effects of existing execution environments create a high barrier to entry, and it’s unlikely that marginal improvements in TPS will be enough to shift developer and user behavior.

This thesis could be invalidated in one of two ways. The first is a rapid influx of new onchain users that pushes demand beyond the current blockspace supply, forcing activity onto newer chains. The second is if these new chains pivot toward specific use cases, transforming their general-purpose execution environments into more specialized ecosystems that offer distinct advantages for certain applications. Either scenario could create an opening for these chains to establish themselves, but absent one of these shifts, they will likely face the same challenges as their predecessors.

Absent one of these shifts, it’s difficult to see how the next batch of L1s and L2s will gain meaningful traction. The supply of blockspace already exceeds demand, and without a compelling reason for users or developers to migrate, these new chains risk following the same trajectory as their 2024 counterparts.

Chris (@capradavis)

Infrastructure should always serve the end user experience. The initial rise of alternative L1s was a direct response to a general-purpose user experience plagued by high transaction costs and slow confirmation times. At the time, the gap in UX between centralized platforms and onchain alternatives fully outweighed the benefits of being onchain for the average user. The leading value proposition of next-generation general-purpose blockchains like Solana and Avalanche was simply making onchain interactions cheaper and faster. This improvement benefited not only users but also developers whose products were hamstrung by fundamentally poor onchain UX.

However, general-purpose chain-level optimization has reached a tipping point where going to market with the same value propositions yields diminishing returns. The wide margin for improvement chains like Solana capitalized on has compressed for new entrants, and the user experience on incumbent L1s and L2s is satisfactory for general-purpose use cases. With the "fast and cheap" value proposition largely addressed, the remaining appeal of new general-purpose chains lies in "community" or the "be early" advantage. It's unlikely that either carries the potential for a seismic shift in demand like the order-of-magnitude improvement in cost and speed introduced by chains like Solana.

That said, there are still areas where launching a new chain to optimize user experience can drive long-term growth. Broadly, to generate sustained demand, I believe new chains need to deliver on one or more of the following value propositions:

  • A killer B2C product that captures and retains user attention.
  • Infrastructure optimizations that deliver an order-of-magnitude better experience for a specific use case.
  • Infrastructure optimizations that unlock an entirely new use case.

Hyperliquid's success can be largely attributed to both 1 and 2. Their B2C perpetuals platform's success was driven by infrastructure optimizations that provided an order-of-magnitude better trading experience than existing offerings. While other variables surely contributed to Hyperliquid's success, I believe these two value propositions were foundational.

Using this framework, I see two new chains with the potential for sustained growth: Abstract and Story Protocol.

Abstract fits the first category, going to market with its "Consumer Portal," a unified front-end that integrates trading, discovery, streaming, and rewards mechanisms. Users onboard via familiar Web2 methods, such as email or social logins, and are immediately immersed in the ecosystem, equipped with all the tools needed for onchain exploration in one place. The product is seriously sticky.

Story Protocol, on the other hand, has developed a multi-layer infrastructure stack to bring the IP economy onchain. Within this stack, execution layer optimizations were necessary to handle IP-specific complexities such as the graph-data structure of royalty distribution. While previous attempts have been made to bring IP onchain, Story's order-of-magnitude improvement essentially positions it as an enabler of a new use case. Although it has a long journey to reach its full potential, if successful, it will provide an objectively more efficient infrastructure for the global IP industry.

While I see a path to success for these two specific cases, they appear to be more the exception than the rule. Unless general-purpose chains pivot to fulfill one of the three demand drivers mentioned above, I believe they’ll likely experience only brief periods of demand driven by "be early" liquidity rotations from users chasing quick returns.

Andrew (@0xSynthesis1)

Putting aside the idea of these upcoming platforms actually gaining traction or actually filling a gap in the current offerings in the market - we should consider whether the market can even sustain new multi-billion dollar launches. According to the CEO of Bybit, we likely had close to $10 billion in long liquidations over the past week as BTC tagged $92,000 again and most altcoins got flushed. The most recent “successful” meta of AI agents has drawn down significantly and may not come back in any meaningful way. TRUMP and MELANIA ultimately pulled a ton of liquidity out of most of the market, and long-held “blue-chip” memes have become a laughing stock. This has all occurred while the average participant was probably under-exposed to BTC while also expecting a bullish Q1 for altcoins. And now we have close to $17 billion in unlocks that the market must absorb from the start of the year until the end of April. When you put this all into context, it is difficult to see where the marginal buyer comes in to support multiple large projects by the end of the quarter.

I think the impact of recent events is also not to be underestimated. The Venice AI launch saw some Aerodrome team members insider trade, along with actual team members selling some supply (albeit a small percentage) on day one. That token trading straight down definitely had an impact on sentiment towards new launches that have perp listings from the get-go. The same might be said for BERA, which despite having aggressively negative funding on perps still traded down after just the first hour of trade. It feels in some ways that the jig is up - insiders can easily hedge their locked spot positions with perps, the market has exhausted the “new launch” trade, and everyone simply wants to extract what little they can from what the market has left.

Does it feel like it’s becoming too consensus to become a BTC maxi after all of these altcoin shenanigans? Probably. But that doesn’t mean the market cannot bleed more or that new launches cannot continue to do poorly (price-wise) for the rest of the quarter.
